🧠 Now Let's Go One Level Deeper

Question...

Dog inherited

eat();

from Animal.

But suppose Dog doesn't eat like every animal.

Suppose Dog wants to print

Dog is eating biscuits

instead of

Animal is eating

Can Dog change the inherited method?

🤔

YES!!

That's called...

🔥 Method Overriding
ELI10

Imagine your father says:

"Every family member eats with a spoon."

But your younger brother says:

"No 😂 I eat with chopsticks."

Same action:

Eat

Different behavior.

This is Method Overriding.

Parent
class Animal {

    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Animal is eating");
    }

}

Child

class Dog extends Animal {

    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Dog is eating biscuits");
    }

}

Notice something?

Same

eat()

Same return type.

Same parameters.

Only output changed.

Main
Dog d = new Dog();

d.eat();

Output

Dog is eating biscuits

Question...

Where did

Animal is eating

go?

😂

Dog replaced it.

That's why it's called

OVERRIDING

Think like this:

Parent

eat()

        ↓

Child says

"No...

I'll do my own version."

        ↓

Parent version replaced.
Real Life Example

Parent

Phone

Call()

Child

iPhone

Call()

Both can call.

But iPhone shows

Beautiful Apple UI

Samsung shows

Samsung UI

Same function.

Different implementation.

Rule of Overriding

The method must have:

✅ Same name

✅ Same parameters

✅ Same return type (for now)

Example
class Animal {

    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes sound");
    }

}

class Dog extends Animal {

    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog says Woof");
    }

}

Main

Dog d = new Dog();

d.sound();

Output

Dog says Woof
